# HTTP File Transfer Server (Sockets, Python)

Implementation of a simple HTTP server using sockets in Python, supporting file upload and download with authentication and performance analysis.

## Context
This project was developed as part of the course Tecnología Digital IV: Redes de Computadoras (UTDT, 2025).

## Authors
- Luca Mateo Fernández Ciatti  
- Candela Sol González Lima  
- Germán Gómez Bonelli  

## My contribution
I contributed to:
- Implementation of request handling logic using sockets
- File upload and download functionality
- HTTP response construction (headers, status codes, content handling)
Additionally, I collaborated with my teammates on the experimental design, performance analysis, and report writing.

Parts of the base code were provided by the course.

## Description
The project consists of a custom HTTP server built directly on top of TCP sockets. It allows:

- File upload via `multipart/form-data`
- File download with proper HTTP headers
- Basic password-based authentication
- Optional gzip compression for file transfer
- QR code generation for easy access to the server

The server parses raw HTTP requests, constructs responses manually, and handles different endpoints.

## Key Features
- Socket-based server
- Manual HTTP parsing (GET/POST)
- File handling and storage
- MIME type detection
- Gzip compression support
- Simple authentication flow

## Experiments
We conducted experiments to analyze:
- File transfer performance
- Impact of gzip compression
- Response time from request to delivery

## Results
- Gzip compression improves transfer time for larger files  
- Manual socket implementation provides insight into HTTP internals  
- Performance depends on file size and network conditions  

## Notes
This project depends on base code provided by the course and may not run standalone.
This repository is intended to showcase the implementation and analysis of networking concepts rather than provide a production-ready server.
